# 2026-04-18

## Node2 GPU Metrics — 2026-04-18
- **13:36 UTC:** Daily GPU aggregation run (cron)
- Script `node1-metrics-aggregate.sh` exists on node2 but references node1 paths → no data produced
- Fallback: aggregated from `node2-gpu-2026-04-18.log` (12,148 samples, ~1h42m)
- GPU 0: avg 84.24W, 29.37% util, 71.5°C, 21,689 MiB VRAM
- GPU 1: avg 81.69W, 28.42% util, 62.6°C, 18,993 MiB VRAM
- Total: 165.93W, 3.982 kWh/day, $0.64/day
- Note: data only covers 01:01–02:43 UTC — incomplete day

## llama-server.service Update (in progress)
- **00:03 UTC:** Jeremy approved llama-server.service changes
- **Plan:**
  - Remove `--flash-attn` (P6000 Turing doesn't support it)
  - `--split-mode tensor --tensor-split 1,1` (replace `-np 2`) — equal GPU work distribution
  - `-np 1` (pipeline parallelism disabled, tensor split handles the work)
  - `--ctx-size 262144` (reduced from 524288/512K)
  - `-b 2048` (reduced from 4096 for faster prefill)
  - `-ub 512` (reduced from 1024 for tighter KV cache)
  - `--threads 28 --threads-batch 28` (added batch-threads)
  - `--parallel 2` (continuous batching, keep at 2)
  - Backup existing service file before changes
- **00:06 UTC:** Jeremy asked if changes were applied on node2
- **00:09 UTC:** Async exec failed (health check failed), changes may not have completed — need to verify on node2

## OpenClaw Timeout Analysis
- LLM HTTP request timeout ~120 seconds (logs showed 125545ms and 122068ms)
- `agents.defaults.timeoutSeconds` defaults to 600 (10 min) — not the issue
- OpenAI SDK `DEFAULT_TIMEOUT = 6e5` (600 sec) — not the issue
- The ~120s timeout is from OpenClaw's internal HTTP client wrapper
- Model: `node2/llamacpp` (Qwen3.5-35B-A3B-Q4_K_M.gguf) with 512K context
- Timed out during heavy context turns (compaction scenarios)

## Current Model Config
- Primary: `node2/llamacpp`
- Fallbacks: `[]` (empty — no auto-failover)
- `compat.supportsUsageInStreaming: true` (set for local model)
